			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Level guide<a name="55529"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 6 04 10:37 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>  So sorry, just tried to  proof read this and it is LONG. No hard feelings here if you just stop anywhere you want<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />
<br />

<br />
I was thinking about this and decided to elaborate a little on my answer, only because I think the way I am soloing is close to what you are looking for but you will also surely gain faster the other ways. I do not know myself, I tried once and did not like it. For reference (I am no very good with stats so no clue if mine are bad or good, but I am pretty sure some are really bad) I am a 50 half-elf bard with a 113 strength, 133 charm, 200 offense, 191 defence, duel wield 125, percussion at level (cant remember the stat). my HP's are about 1500 and my mana is about 1400.  I never get any buffs, temp or otherwise (I happily accept them most times, but I don't see that many people the area's I hang in).  My equipment is decent for my level (this is my main) and would never be considered twinked by any definition.  I have a thundrous drum of dark rites(?) primary, and a (can't remember) piercing weapon (no proc).
<br />

<br />
   If one can not take more than a few good hits (frost giant type hits) I definately suggest getting temp. And I probably wouldn't be impressed by the twinked bard myself ~wink~. 
<br />

<br />
   The reason I suggested detailed hunting guides is because I like to do this where there is little chance running into more than one or two people (I enjoy the company, but not when I am a little busy).  I also do not like to many details, I like the fun of exploring and the possibility of death. Once I die it is a different story for that zone lol. If I were to start a bard over again, I would walk basically the same path, but I would have done it a little differently. I can not say faster because I love to goof off too, I spend lots of time just running the countryside to see the sights.
<br />

<br />
     I am just going to use a recent fun (for me anyway lol) battle to illustrate my point, only because the Mob names and zone can be interchanged depending on your level. I went to the Eastern Wastes at level 46 and set up &quot;camp&quot; near Icefang. Korrigan (or whatever the heck his name is) gave me quite a start during a quiet moment. I also knew by now (sort of) first hand where NOT to run (nasty little death squad's , ya know?)  and it is not far from Icefang.
<br />

<br />
   Just over the hill to the right (I was standing in front of icefang) there is a hill, then a valley, then a hill. The Sleepers tomb (I think) lies just beyond. In the first valley there is usually a giant or two, a rhino sometimes......and some other critters at times also.
<br />

<br />
     I ran over the first hill and slowed a giant in the valley and dropped 2 chants on him and led the way over the second hill (keeping in mind the slow would drop shortly). Over the next hill is a kind of flattened area, a dangerous, but fun, place to watch the titons of the Wastes battle. To my delight 2 rhinos stood a good distance apart so I turned and slowed the giant again and dropped 2 more chants. One Rhino was nearby and I charmed him quickly and sicced him on the frost giant, who I dropped another slow on. I ran to the next rhino and slowed him, dropped 2 and started back (slowly, kept up the slow chant twist) I was not paying good enough attention and picked up a LB wolf (all others are DB). I sing slow and 2 for the wolf and pick back up on my really mad (by now) rhino shadow.
<br />

<br />
The other pet is rhino doing a pretty good job, but giant is still only 30% and charm will break soon. Meanwhile wolf breaks my slow...rhino breaks my slow....charm breaks....another wolf adds.....another wolf adds.....charm rhino....slow biggest to lowest (ack, who the heck cares slow first target).....charm rhino....Attack giant, Pet rhino...ATTACK I SAID........slow other rhino tagging me in the behind now....run back into other wolves....slow a wolf....the beat goes on....charm breaks......finally giant down, 2 rhinos fighting.....hateful freaking wolves in control and dying. Charm breaks.......run around even more.....wolves drop.... Sigh, I am finally back at Icefang. My health is 43%, my mana 50% (full at start). 
<br />

<br />
    For brevity ~smile~ I have left out the MANY Selo's casts and the just plain circling minutes as I tried to get the various critters together enough to try to sing a few down. Not to metion I did not do this at Icefang, I did it in the first valley with a variety of potential adds that I had to avoid at the same time (makes it much more interesting). I could not tell you what the experience was for my character, but I do know it was a whole lot of fun for me.
<br />

<br />
   I generally continue pulling one or two for a while after hitting 50% or so in mana, or just afk for a little while and practice my Wind. If I continue pulling, I blow mana if I get in a little trouble, otherwise I just sing one or two of them near Icefang. If I need weapon exp, I will sing snare and just melee one critter down when he gets low (the big guys take a while). When my mana is at the level I want (and if I have the energy), I go find another group to fight about who gets to kill me first<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />.  Not sure where I will go next, but the method will be similar.
<br />

<br />
    I would be considered a casual player I guess, mainly because my bard is 2 and a half years old now (she was started well before Luclin). But I have played and beta tested games a lot of games during that time also. I always come back to Norrath though, and I surely have had a lot of fun there. I have a 31 human SK also, she is fun but she could never touch the bard.
<br />

<br />
Good hunting to all 
<br />

<br />

